twist on central themes of American labor and working-class history, Leon Fink examines how the American conceptualization of free labor played out in iconic industrial strikes, and how "freedom" in the workplace became overwhelmingly tilted toward individual property rights at the expense of larger community standards. He investigates the legal and intellectual centers of progressive thought, situating American policy actions within an international context. In particular, he traces the development of American socialism, which appealed to a young generation by virtue of its very un-American roots and influences.The Long Gilded Age offers both a transnational and comparative look at a formative era in American political development, placing this tumultuous period within a worldwide confrontation between the capitalist marketplace and social transformation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aCapitalismzUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aCapitalismzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aGlobalizationxHistoryy19th century. 0aGlobalizationxHistoryy20th century. 0aLaborzUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aLaborzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 4aAmerican Studies. 7aHISTORY / United States / 19th Century.2bisacsh  aAmerican History.  aAmerican Studies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2015z9783110439687oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2015z9783110438635oZDB-23-DEG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Pennsylvania Press Complete Package 2014-2015z978311066593240uhttps://doi.org/10.9783/978081229203940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780812292039423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780812292039.jpg  a978-3-11-066593-2  University of Pennsylvania Press